# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: account-abstraction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A **cryptocurrency wallet** is a device, physical medium, program or an online service which stores the public and/or private keys for cryptocurrency transactions.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In addition to this basic function of storing the keys, a cryptocurrency wallet more often offers the functionality of encrypting and/or signing information.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Signing can for example result in executing a smart contract, a cryptocurrency transaction (see "bitcoin transaction" image), identification, or legally signing a 'document' (see "application form" image).
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In 2008 bitcoin was introduced as the first cryptocurrency following the principle outlined by Satoshi Nakamoto in the paper “Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System.” The project was described as an electronic payment system using cryptographic proof instead of trust.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] It also mentioned using cryptographic proof to verify and record transactions on a blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The first wallet program, simply named *Bitcoin*, and sometimes referred to as the *Satoshi client*, was released in January 2009 by Satoshi Nakamoto as open-source software.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In version 0.5 the client moved from the wxWidgets user interface toolkit to Qt, and the whole bundle was referred to as *Bitcoin-Qt*.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] After the release of version 0.9, the software bundle was renamed *Bitcoin Core* to distinguish itself from the underlying network.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Bitcoin Core is, perhaps, the best known implementation or client.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Forks of Bitcoin Core exist, such as Bitcoin XT, Bitcoin Unlimited, and Parity Bitcoin.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Software wallets is a broad category of software applications that allow users to manage and transfer digital assets, and sign messages.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] They can be run as desktop apps, mobile apps, web extensions, or web wallets.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] There are several modes in which software wallets can operate.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] They have an inverse relationship with regard to trustlessness and computational requirements.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Third-party internet services called *online wallets* or *webwallets* offer similar functionality but may be easier to use.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In this case, credentials to access funds are stored with the online wallet provider rather than on the user's hardware.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] As a result, the user must have complete trust in the online wallet provider.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A malicious provider or a breach in server security may cause entrusted crypto to be stolen.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] An example of such a security breach occurred with Mt.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A paper wallet with the address visible for adding or checking stored funds.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The part of the page containing the private key is folded over and sealed.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A part of the address is visible through a transparent part of the hologram.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] "Cold storage" simply means keeping the private keys out of reach of hackers by storing or generating them on a device that is not connected to the internet.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The credentials necessary to spend crypto can be stored offline in a number of different ways, from simple paper printouts of private keys, to specialized hardware wallets.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A paper wallet is created with a keypair generated on a computer with no internet connection; the private key is written or printed onto the paper and then erased from the computer.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The paper wallet can then be stored in a safe physical location for later retrieval.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Physical wallets can also take the form of metal token coins with a private key accessible under a security hologram in a recess struck on the reverse side.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The security hologram self-destructs when removed from the token, showing that the private key has been accessed.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Originally, these tokens were struck in brass and other base metals, but later used precious metals as bitcoin grew in value and popularity.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Coins with stored face value as high as ₿1,000 have been struck in gold.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The British Museum's coin collection includes four specimens from the earliest series of funded bitcoin tokens; one is currently on display in the museum's money gallery.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In 2013, a Utah manufacturer of these tokens was ordered by the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) to register as a money services business before producing any more funded bitcoin tokens.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A hardware "wallet" is a small and portable computer peripheral that signs transactions as requested by the user.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] These devices store private keys and carry out signing and encryption internally, and do not share any sensitive information with the host computer except already signed (and thus unalterable) transactions.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Because hardware wallets never expose their private keys, even computers that may be compromised by malware do not have a vector to access or steal them.The user sets a passcode when setting up a hardware signer.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] As hardware signers are tamper-resistant, without the passcode the assets cannot be accessed.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In contrast to simple cryptocurrency wallets requiring just one party to sign a transaction, multi-sig wallets require multiple parties to sign a transaction.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Multisignature wallets are designed to increase security by requiring a predefined threshold of signatures from independent private keys to authorize any transaction.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In deterministic multisig wallets, a hierarchy of keys (often following a dedicated path such as `m/48'`) allows multiple participants to derive compatible public keys from a single master seed while maintaining independent private key control.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] There are various use cases for multisignature wallets, including enhanced security, treasury management, partnership management, escrow services, inheritance planning, regulatory compliance and backup recovery.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A cryptocurrency wallet works by a theoretical or random number being generated and used with a length that depends on the algorithm size of the cryptocurrency's technology requirements.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The number is converted to a private key using the specific requirements of the cryptocurrency cryptography algorithm requirement.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A public key is then generated from the private key using whichever cryptographic algorithm is required.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The private key is used by the owner to access and send cryptocurrency and is private to the owner, whereas the public key is to be shared to any third party to receive cryptocurrency.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Up to this stage no computer or electronic device is required and all key pairs can be mathematically derived and written down by hand.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The private key and public key pair (known as an address) are not known by the blockchain or anyone else.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The blockchain will only record the transaction of the public address when cryptocurrency is sent to it, thus recording in the blockchain ledger the transaction of the public address.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Collision (two or more wallets having the same private key) is theoretically possible, since keys can be generated without being used for transactions, and are therefore offline until recorded in the blockchain ledger.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] However, this possibility is effectively negated because the theoretical probability of two or more private keys being the same is extremely low.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The number of possible wallets and thus private keys is extremely high, so duplicating or hacking a certain key would be inconceivable.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In modern convention a seed phrase is now utilised which is a random 12 to 24 (or even greater) list of dictionary words which is an unencrypted form of the private key.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] (Words are easier to memorize than numerals).
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] When online, exchange and hardware wallets are generated using random numbers, and the user is asked to supply a seed phrase.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] If the wallet is misplaced, damaged or compromised, the seed phrase can be used to re-access the wallet and associated keys and cryptocurrency *in toto*.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A number of technologies known as wallets exist that store the key value pair of private and public key known as wallets.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A wallet hosts the details of the key pair making cryptocurrency transactions possible.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Multiple methods exist for storing keys or seeds in a wallet.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A *brainwallet* or *brain wallet* is a type of wallet in which one memorizes a passcode (a private key or seed phrase).
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Brainwallets may be attractive due to plausible deniability or protection against governmental seizure, but are vulnerable to password guessing (especially large-scale offline guessing).
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Several hundred brainwallets exist on the Bitcoin blockchain, but most of them have been drained, sometimes repeatedly.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] DApp browsers are specialized software that supports decentralized applications.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] DApp browsers are considered to be the browsers of Web3 and are the gateway to access the decentralized applications which are based on blockchain technology.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] That means all DApp browsers must have a unique code system to unify all the different codes of the DApps.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] While crypto wallets are focused on the exchange, purchase, sale of digital assets and support narrowly targeted applications, the browsers support different kinds of applications of various formats, including exchange, games, NFTs marketplaces, etc.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In addition to the basic function of storing the keys, a cryptocurrency wallet may also have one or more of the following characteristics.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A simple cryptocurrency wallet contains pairs of public and private cryptographic keys.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The keys can be used to track ownership, receipt or spend cryptocurrencies.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A public key allows others to make payments to the address derived from it, whereas a private key enables the spending of cryptocurrency from that address.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The cryptocurrency itself is not in the wallet.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In the case of bitcoin and cryptocurrencies derived from it, the cryptocurrency is decentrally stored and maintained in a publicly available distributed ledger called the *blockchain*.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Multi-chain wallets are designed to support multiple blockchain networks, enabling users to store, manage, and transact different types of cryptocurrencies from a single interface.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Unlike single-chain wallets, which are limited to a specific blockchain, multi-chain wallets provide a unified experience for handling various assets.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] These wallets enhance convenience and security by reducing the need for multiple wallet applications and providing integrated features for multiple digital assets.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Popular multi-chain wallets include Trust Wallet, Klever Wallet and Exodus, each offering unique features and support for multiple blockchains, therefore, hundreds of cryptocurrencies.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Some wallets are specifically designed to be compatible with a framework.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The European Union is creating an eIDAS compatible European Self-Sovereign Identity Framework (ESSIF) which runs on the European Blockchain Services Infrastructure (EBSI).
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The EBSI wallet is designed to (securely) provide information, an eID and to sign 'transactions'.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A sequential deterministic wallet utilizes a simple method of generating addresses from a known starting string or "seed".
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] This would utilize a cryptographic hash function, e.g.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] SHA-256 (seed + n), where n is an ASCII-coded number that starts from 1 and increments as additional keys are needed.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] The hierarchical deterministic (HD) wallet was publicly described in BIP32.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] As a deterministic wallet, it derives keys from a single master root seed, but instead of having a single "chain" of key pairs, an HD wallet supports multiple independent key pair chains.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] This allows a single seed to be used to generate an entire tree of key pairs with a stratified structure.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] BIP39 proposed the use of a set of human-readable words to derive the seed used to generate a wallet’s master private key.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] This mnemonic phrase allows for easier wallet backup and recovery, due to all keys of a wallet being derivable from a single plaintext string.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In a non-deterministic wallet, each key is randomly generated independently and is not derived from a common seed.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Therefore, any backups of the wallet must store each and every private key used as an address, as well as a buffer of future keys that may have already been issued as addresses but have not yet received payments.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A wallet can also have known or unknown vulnerabilities.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A supply chain attack or side-channel attack are ways of introducing vulnerabilities.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In extreme cases even a computer which is not connected to any network can be hacked.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] To mitigate the risk of crypto wallet hacking, one can choose for a cold wallet, which remains offline and disconnected from the internet.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] A cold wallet refers to a physical device, such as a pen drive, that is utilized as a secure storage medium for transferring money from a hot wallet.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] When using a merchant site that accepts server-side digital wallets, customers enter their name, payment, and delivery information.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Following the purchase, the customer is requested to register for a wallet with a user name and password for future purchases.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Wallets are free for consumers but cost retailers.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] Wallet sellers may receive a portion of merchant purchases made through their wallets.
[src:account-abstraction/cryptocurrency-wallet] In other circumstances, digital wallet vendors conduct cardholder-merchant transactions for a set fee.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] An Ethereum account is an entity with an ether (ETH) balance that can send messages on Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] Accounts can be user-controlled or deployed as smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] To help you better understand this page, we recommend you first read through our introduction to Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] An account is made up of a pair of cryptographic keys: public and private.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] They help prove that a transaction was actually signed by the sender and prevent forgeries.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] Your private key is what you use to sign transactions, so it grants you custody over the funds associated with your account.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] You never really hold cryptocurrency, you hold private keys – the funds are always on Ethereum's ledger.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] This prevents malicious actors from broadcasting fake transactions because you can always verify the sender of a transaction.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] If Alice wants to send ether from her own account to Bob’s account, Alice needs to create a transaction request and send it out to the network for verification.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] Ethereum’s usage of public-key cryptography ensures that Alice can prove that she originally initiated the transaction request.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] Without cryptographic mechanisms, a malicious adversary Eve could simply publicly broadcast a request that looks something like “send 5 ETH from Alice’s account to Eve’s account,” and no one would be able to verify that it didn’t come from Alice.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] When you want to create an account, most libraries will generate you a random private key.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] A private key is made up of 64 hex characters and can be encrypted with a password.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] The public key is generated from the private key using the Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (opens in a new tab).
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] You get a public address for your account by taking the last 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the public key and adding `0x` to the beginning.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] This means an Externally owned account (EOA) has a 42-character address (20-byte segment which is 40 hexadecimal characters plus the `0x` prefix).
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] The following example shows how to use a signing tool called Clef (opens in a new tab) to generate a new account.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] Clef is an account management and signing tool that comes bundled with the Ethereum client, Geth (opens in a new tab).
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] The `clef newaccount` command creates a new key pair and saves them in an encrypted keystore.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] It is possible to derive new public keys from your private key, but you cannot derive a private key from public keys.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] It is vital to keep your private keys safe and, as the name suggests, **PRIVATE**.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] You need a private key to sign messages and transactions which output a signature.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] Others can then take the signature to derive your public key, proving the author of the message.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] In your application, you can use a JavaScript library to send transactions to the network.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] The contract address is usually given when a contract is deployed to the Ethereum Blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] The address comes from the creator's address and the number of transactions sent from that address (the “nonce”).
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] There is also another type of key in Ethereum, introduced when Ethereum switched from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake based consensus.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] These are 'BLS' keys and they are used to identify validators.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] These keys can be efficiently aggregated to reduce the bandwidth required for the network to come to consensus.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] Without this key aggregation the minimum stake for a validator would be much higher.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] A wallet is an interface or application that lets you interact with your Ethereum account, either an externally-owned account or a contract account.
[src:account-abstraction/developers-accounts] Watch Austin walk you through hash functions, and key pairs.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:account-abstraction/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:account-abstraction/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] A "smart contract" is simply a program that runs on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] It's a collection of code (its functions) and data (its state) that resides at a specific address on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Smart contracts are a type of Ethereum account.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] This means they have a balance and can be the target of transactions.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] However they're not controlled by a user, instead they are deployed to the network and run as programmed.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] User accounts can then interact with a smart contract by submitting transactions that execute a function defined on the smart contract.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Smart contracts can define rules, like a regular contract, and automatically enforce them via the code.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Smart contracts cannot be deleted by default, and interactions with them are irreversible.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] If you're just getting started or looking for a less technical introduction, we recommend our introduction to smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Make sure you've read up on accounts, transactions and the Ethereum virtual machine before jumping into the world of smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Perhaps the best metaphor for a smart contract is a vending machine, as described by Nick Szabo (opens in a new tab).
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] With the right inputs, a certain output is guaranteed.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] This logic is programmed into the vending machine.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] A smart contract, like a vending machine, has logic programmed into it.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Like how a vending machine removes the need for a vendor employee, smart contracts can replace intermediaries in many industries.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Anyone can write a smart contract and deploy it to the network.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] You just need to learn how to code in a smart contract language, and have enough ETH to deploy your contract.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Deploying a smart contract is technically a transaction, so you need to pay gas in the same way you need to pay gas for a simple ETH transfer.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] However, gas costs for contract deployment are far higher.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] However, they must be compiled before they can be deployed so that Ethereum's virtual machine can interpret and store the contract.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Smart contracts are public on Ethereum and can be thought of as open APIs.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] This means you can call other smart contracts in your own smart contract to greatly extend what's possible.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Contracts can even deploy other contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Learn more about smart contract composability.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Smart contracts alone cannot get information about "real-world" events because they can't retrieve data from offchain sources.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] This means they can't respond to events in the real world.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Relying on external information could jeopardise consensus, which is important for security and decentralization.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] However, it is important for blockchain applications to be able to use offchain data.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] The solution is oracles which are tools that ingest offchain data and make it available to smart contracts.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Another limitation of smart contracts is the maximum contract size.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] A smart contract can be a maximum of 24KB or it will run out of gas.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] This can be circumnavigated by using The Diamond Pattern (opens in a new tab).
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Multisig (multiple-signature) contracts are smart contract accounts that require multiple valid signatures to execute a transaction.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] This is very useful for avoiding single points of failure for contracts holding substantial amounts of ether or other tokens.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Multisigs also divide responsibility for contract execution and key management between multiple parties and prevent the loss of a single private key leading to irreversible loss of funds.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] For these reasons, multisig contracts can be used for simple DAO governance.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] Multisigs require N signatures out of M possible acceptable signatures (where N ≤ M, and M > 1) in order to execute.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] A 4/7 multisig requires four out of seven possible valid signatures.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] This means the funds are still retrievable even if three signatures are lost.
[src:account-abstraction/smart-contracts] In this case, it also means that the majority of key-holders must agree and sign in order for the contract to execute.
